body:
### Component

Forge

### Have you ensured that all of these are up to date?

- [X] Foundry
- [X] Foundryup

### What version of Foundry are you on?

forge 0.2.0 (bff4ed9 2023-08-28T00:24:09.226668296Z)

### What command(s) is the bug in?

forge test --fork-url <RPC_ENDPOINT>

### Operating System

Linux

### Describe the bug

I just spotted this bug in the wild while running MakerDAO's [Spell Test suite](https://github.com/makerdao/spells-goerli/blob/0bc45005e3afe60bfda47121c4337fbb85b40653/src/DssSpell.t.base.sol#L283-L302).

Relevant part of the code:

```solidity
    function setUp() public {
        setValues(address(chief));

        spellValues.deployed_spell_created = spellValues.deployed_spell != address(0) ? spellValues.deployed_spell_created : block.timestamp;
        _castPreviousSpell();

        // ------------- From here ----------------------
        spell = spellValues.deployed_spell != address(0) ?
            DssSpell(spellValues.deployed_spell) : new DssSpell();

        if (spellValues.deployed_spell_block != 0 && spell.eta() != 0) {
            // if we have a deployed spell in the config
            // we want to roll our fork to the block where it was deployed
            // this means the test suite will continue to accurately pass/fail
            // even if mainnet has already scheduled/cast the spell
            vm.makePersistent(address(this));
            vm.makePersistent(address(rates));
            vm.makePersistent(address(addr));
            vm.makePersistent(address(deployers));
            vm.rollFork(spellValues.deployed_spell_block);
        }
    }
```

Spells have an `eta` and a `done` storage variables.

Apparently, any "hot" storage variable is not reset after `rollFork`, like if we had called `vm.makePersistent()` on it.

If I log both variables _before_ and _after_ `rollFork`, they have the same value:

```solidity
        if (spellValues.deployed_spell_block != 0 && spell.eta() != 0) {
            console2.log("Before `rollFork`: eta = %d, done = %b", spell.eta(), spell.done());

            // if we have a deployed spell in the config
            // we want to roll our fork to the block where it was deployed
            // this means the test suite will continue to accurately pass/fail
            // even if mainnet has already scheduled/cast the spell
            vm.makePersistent(address(this));
            vm.makePersistent(address(rates));
            vm.makePersistent(address(addr));
            vm.makePersistent(address(deployers));
            vm.rollFork(spellValues.deployed_spell_block);

            console2.log("After `rollFork`: eta = %d, done = %b", spell.eta(), spell.done());
        }
```

Result shows both wrong:

```
Logs:
  Before `rollFork`: eta = 1693238220, done = b true
  After `rollFork`: eta = 1693238220, done = b true
```

If I remove the log from _before_, `done` is now correct (it has not been accessed), however `eta` is still incorrect, because it was accessed in the conditional:

```solidity
        //                                                  +---- `eta` accessed here:
        //                                                  v
        if (spellValues.deployed_spell_block != 0 && spell.eta() != 0) {
            // if we have a deployed spell in the config
            // we want to roll our fork to the block where it was deployed
            // this means the test suite will continue to accurately pass/fail
            // even if mainnet has already scheduled/cast the spell
            vm.makePersistent(address(this));
            vm.makePersistent(address(rates));
            vm.makePersistent(address(addr));
            vm.makePersistent(address(deployers));
            vm.rollFork(spellValues.deployed_spell_block);

            console2.log("After `rollFork`: eta = %d, done = %b", spell.eta(), spell.done());
        }
```

Result shows `done` correct and `eta` wrong:

```
Logs:
  eta = 1693238220, done = b false
```

If I remove `eta` from the conditional and log it only after `rollFork`, it works as expected:

```
        if (spellValues.deployed_spell_block != 0) {
            // if we have a deployed spell in the config
            // we want to roll our fork to the block where it was deployed
            // this means the test suite will continue to accurately pass/fail
            // even if mainnet has already scheduled/cast the spell
            vm.makePersistent(address(this));
            vm.makePersistent(address(rates));
            vm.makePersistent(address(addr));
            vm.makePersistent(address(deployers));
            vm.rollFork(spellValues.deployed_spell_block);

            console2.log("After `rollFork`: eta = %d, done = %b", spell.eta(), spell.done());
        }
```

Result with both correct:
```
Logs:
  eta = 0, done = b false
```

This looks like an unexpected behavior.

Please reach out to me if you need help running that test suite, but after setting `ETH_RPC_URL`, you can just call `make test match="testOnTime"`.

@mds1 yes i was able to test this

```solidity
     function setUp() public {
        // deploys at current fork block
        // using `--rpc-url` 
        counter = new Counter();
        counter.increment();
    }

    function testRoll() public {
        assertEq(counter.number(), 100);

        counter.setNumber(100);

        assertEq(counter.number(), 100);

        vm.rollFork(block.number - 100);

        assertEq(counter.number(), 100);
    }

```

I think this makes sense because all state changes (reads or writes) end up in the `journaled_state` and would then be copied over for subsequent calls in the function. I believe REVM trys to load state from there first.

And in ops case since this is the `setup` function all of this would then get written to the CacheDb since it commits its state, meaning it would persist across tests. (the journaled state is thrown away between tests/setup).

I think i like option 4, and i agree snapshot/revert seems like the right call here

@mattsse 

imo a bigger issue that is related and i could see people getting confused about is that if you do an sload on `address(n)` at `block=t`, and then roll **forward** to `block=t+x < current_block` in subsequent calls it will still be the old value until the journaled state is dropped, for example within tests or within the setup function.

not sure if this actually gets persisted in the cacheDB if its in setupt (is it marked touched from an sload?)
